{"term":"1956","caseName":"Achilli v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/430","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - May 02, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13186","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm including my remarks with respect to the (Inaudible) the application of 3616.","start":0,"stop":11.407,"duration":11.41},{"text":"I think it is fair to say that the purposes applying that particular section were to -- to meet the protest of the District Courts, the various District Courts and the United States Attorneys in the various districts.","start":11.407,"stop":29.194,"duration":17.79},{"text":"And to ameliorate a lot of the small taxpayer who was being subjected to a felony prosecution and summonses where the tax involved was as low as a $100 or a $150.","start":29.194,"stop":43.911,"duration":14.72}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- I suppose have put in your brief the names of those cases and the amounts involved in them substantially to the statement?","start":43.911,"stop":55.349,"duration":11.44}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":55.349,"stop":56.064,"duration":0.72},{"text":"We haven't got the names of the cases.","start":56.064,"stop":57.896,"duration":1.83},{"text":"We have a reference of the total amounts of the cases.","start":57.896,"stop":60.893,"duration":3},{"text":"They have the list of the amounts involved.","start":60.893,"stop":63.167,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If this is material, I should think, might be wise to have all record of all those cases during that period of time with the name where they were tried?","start":63.167,"stop":75.743,"duration":12.58}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, we could give you --","start":75.743,"stop":76.31,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If I presume it would be very easy because you know.","start":76.31,"stop":78.871,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":78.871,"stop":80.28,"duration":1.41},{"text":"We could give you the -- I think that we can state it as a general proposition that those prosecutions involved less than a $1000 in income.","start":80.28,"stop":97.775,"duration":17.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you said less than hundreds?","start":97.775,"stop":99.353,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That was tax, sir.","start":99.353,"stop":100.603,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Tax.","start":100.603,"stop":101.823,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Less than a $1000 in income and of course considerably below that in tax.","start":101.823,"stop":107.088,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's all of them?","start":107.088,"stop":109.22,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I wouldn't want to say that there never has been an exception to that but that has been the general practice.","start":109.22,"stop":117.484,"duration":8.26},{"text":"And as far as the amounts involved, I haven't actually made a study of the cases myself to determine whether it's a $100 or $200 or $300 or $400 but I think I can fairly say and we will be glad to furnish whatever he would like in that respect that the amounts involved were not large.","start":117.484,"stop":141.332,"duration":23.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you -- if you are right in your present position, then no matter how small, they would all have -- the prosecution would all have to be begun by -- before a grand jury and by indictment?","start":141.332,"stop":151.801,"duration":10.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor, if 3616 has no application in this area.","start":151.801,"stop":158.563,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would that -- would those figures after they reflect the amount of the tax that had been evaded or -- or would they be doing as they sometimes do in other cases, say in an embezzlement case where $50,000 has been embezzled, maybe they'll only charge a $1000 or $500 because those items are clear to make that (Voice Overlap) --","start":158.563,"stop":185.486,"duration":26.92}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":185.486,"stop":185.819,"duration":0.33},{"text":"Well, that I think is true in almost every criminal tax case.","start":185.819,"stop":190.799,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":190.799,"stop":191.221,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Not every case but in most of them, you have what they call the prosecutor of the net income for prosecution purposes, and that is very frequently less than -- but for civil -- what they would allege for civil purposes.","start":191.221,"stop":207.642,"duration":16.42},{"text":"So what I'm talking about is the amount alleged for criminal purposes.","start":207.642,"stop":212,"duration":4.36},{"text":"Now, a very large percentage of these small cases where the result of the claim of a fictitious defendant where a person would claim that John Jones and Richard Rowe were defendants when actually there was no such person as John Jones or Richard Rowe.","start":212,"stop":232.585,"duration":20.59},{"text":"And the amount of the exemption being $600 for each of them and would result in a fairly small tax and yet the fraud would be so clear cut that it was difficult to overlook at.","start":232.585,"stop":250.433,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say --","start":250.433,"stop":250.548,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the -- the purpose in bringing these prosecutions under Section 3616 was I think to --","start":250.548,"stop":261.663,"duration":11.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that material here?","start":261.663,"stop":264.221,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":264.221,"stop":264.611,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's material, I think if you're going to state that they're all small and -- but the purpose was it'd be wiser if you give us a list because I don't think it's material.","start":264.611,"stop":276.97,"duration":12.36},{"text":"But if it is material, I think we should be given a list.","start":276.97,"stop":280.02,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think it's material either, Your Honor --","start":280.02,"stop":281.478,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in the general sense but all.","start":281.478,"stop":283.755,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's material either.","start":283.755,"stop":285.688,"duration":1.93},{"text":"What I'm saying here is by way of background as to how the department got embarked on this particular course of action.","start":285.688,"stop":294.428,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Number of these cases, I think you told us before recess where prosecuted by information of an indictment?","start":294.428,"stop":299.884,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":299.884,"stop":300.274,"duration":0.39},{"text":"I would say the majority of them -- the large majority of them -- there were of course some by indictment.","start":300.274,"stop":306.604,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"With this new position, the Government is correct, what's the Government's position in relation to people prosecuted by and large?","start":306.604,"stop":313.549,"duration":6.94},{"text":"Now, it shouldn't have been prosecuted at all.","start":313.549,"stop":316.586,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course that question isn't decided as yet whether or not they should have been prosecuted at all.","start":316.586,"stop":321.489,"duration":4.9},{"text":"We don't have before us a Section 3616 case.","start":321.489,"stop":326.648,"duration":5.16},{"text":"Now, in concluding these -- these remarks with respect to 3616, I think I should say that whether or not, the Government proceeded correctly under the section it invoked as a matter that we just don't know or prosecutions under that section have been held in advance pending the outcome of this proceeding.","start":326.648,"stop":355.986,"duration":29.34},{"text":"And as far as this case is concerned, it is a 145 (b) case and we think that the issue as to a 3616 case ought to be resolved when such a case comes before this Court.","start":355.986,"stop":372.777,"duration":16.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's just the same -- I wouldn't decide on that basis that a 3616 does apply to income tax cases.","start":372.777,"stop":384.452,"duration":11.68},{"text":"That this man could have been prosecuted under either.","start":384.452,"stop":388.477,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there again, that question is not before the Court because he was prosecuted under Section 145 (b).","start":388.477,"stop":395.495,"duration":7.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand he were.","start":395.495,"stop":397.499,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if your -- I do not know what -- I don't -- I don't quite appreciate your answer.","start":397.499,"stop":401.976,"duration":4.48},{"text":"If the position now taken by the Government is correct, then you -- then your answer to Justice Black's question is, he couldn't be prosecuted in the 3616 and he's properly prosecuted by the only section under which he could be prosecuted 145 (b).","start":401.976,"stop":416.836,"duration":14.86},{"text":"Is that correct?","start":416.836,"stop":418.009,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that's correct.","start":418.009,"stop":419.243,"duration":1.23},{"text":"Of course in the Moran case, being the --","start":419.243,"stop":420.802,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean, if your position is correct.","start":420.802,"stop":422.857,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":422.857,"stop":423.24,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was my hypothesis --","start":423.24,"stop":423.481,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":423.481,"stop":423.916,"duration":0.44},{"text":"And suppose your position is wrong.","start":423.916,"stop":426.39,"duration":2.47},{"text":"And suppose that both statutes apply.","start":426.39,"stop":431.575,"duration":5.19},{"text":"We don't understand what you say on page 33 that in this case as in Berra and that proves that he willfully attempted to raise by filing a false return as identical of that required prove that he filed a false return with attempt to evade in violation of 3616?","start":431.575,"stop":450.658,"duration":19.08},{"text":"That's what the Government argued in Berra.","start":450.658,"stop":452.457,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":452.457,"stop":454.136,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Well, Your Honor, we have a question here as to whether the -- there are one or two offenses involved.","start":454.136,"stop":459.778,"duration":5.64},{"text":"Now, the language of the Second Circuit in the Moran case would seem to imply that there are two offenses involved here because each of the sections requires proof of an act which is not required for the other.","start":459.778,"stop":473.47,"duration":13.69},{"text":"But we think that you don't have to resolve that question because even if there are only one offense here, involved here, we think there's nothing to preclude the Court from applying under -- from proceeding under the felony statute as against the misdemeanor statute.","start":473.47,"stop":492.015,"duration":18.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if there -- there are two offenses when there is no problem of choice by a prosecutor with different terms, is there?","start":492.015,"stop":502.355,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- we all think of it in terms of choice for the prosecutor Your Honor.","start":502.355,"stop":506.713,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- I don't mean to say -- but the problem doesn't arise.","start":506.713,"stop":511.183,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":511.183,"stop":511.893,"duration":0.71},{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":511.893,"stop":512.47,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":512.47,"stop":513.501,"duration":1.03},{"text":"I know that you don't.","start":513.501,"stop":514.11,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The question I was asking was in the Berra case, the Government's brief said this as I quote it to the oral argument.","start":514.11,"stop":522.761,"duration":8.65},{"text":"Section 145 (b), 3616 (a) overlap a broad area illustrated by the present case.","start":522.761,"stop":531.308,"duration":8.55},{"text":"Is that proved here?","start":531.308,"stop":536.012,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Where are you reading from?","start":536.012,"stop":537.045,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I was reading from the Government's brief in the Berra case.","start":537.045,"stop":541.203,"duration":4.16},{"text":"Is that true here what the Government said about the Berra case?","start":541.203,"stop":546.868,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is true to the extent that you have two offenses which the same act could violate.","start":546.868,"stop":560.391,"duration":13.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well do -- do this act in this case, if you are wrong and if you can prosecute under either, are there searches to justify a prosecution under both?","start":560.391,"stop":573.045,"duration":12.65}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, our position is that you don't have to decide that question.","start":573.045,"stop":576.881,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but maybe we might disagree with that.","start":576.881,"stop":581.223,"duration":4.34},{"text":"Suppose we do, are we to try it on the basis that if 3616 and 145 (a) applied, these overlap as we'd say in the case and the Berra case.","start":581.223,"stop":593.243,"duration":12.02}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that --","start":593.243,"stop":594.215,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the facts.","start":594.215,"stop":597.118,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"I just can't say as to what would be done in that situation.","start":597.118,"stop":600.755,"duration":3.64},{"text":"It hasn't been done in the past.","start":600.755,"stop":602.912,"duration":2.16},{"text":"There haven't been prosecutions under both sections.","start":602.912,"stop":605.633,"duration":2.72},{"text":"I think it's highly unlikely there would be.","start":605.633,"stop":607.777,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't ask -- I didn't ask you that question.","start":607.777,"stop":610.521,"duration":2.74},{"text":"There was a very simple statement in connection with the Berra prosecution which was presented to us and it was admitted by the Government that under the facts in that case as 3616 was then construed, the defendant could be prosecuted under either.","start":610.521,"stop":630.754,"duration":20.23},{"text":"Is that the case here with reference to these facts?","start":630.754,"stop":636.157,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":636.157,"stop":636.698,"duration":0.54},{"text":"I think it is.","start":636.698,"stop":638.436,"duration":1.74},{"text":"In other words, when we brought the 145 (b) prosecution, it is conceivable that the Court could have found the defendant guilty under 3616 --","start":638.436,"stop":648.769,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it conceivable or is it your judgment it could?","start":648.769,"stop":651.593,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"It could have.","start":651.593,"stop":652.735,"duration":1.14},{"text":"It could have, Your Honor.","start":652.735,"stop":655.984,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let -- let's assume that the two statutes are identical and you could have prosecuted under either, what's the Government's position on that question?","start":655.984,"stop":670.944,"duration":14.96}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That we could have prosecuted under either?","start":670.944,"stop":672.838,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":672.838,"stop":673.67,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":673.67,"stop":673.734,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You could've captioned this indictment 3616 (a) or 145 (b).","start":673.734,"stop":679.647,"duration":5.91},{"text":"Now, what would --","start":679.647,"stop":680.257,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well we believe it is a matter within the discretion of the Court that the Court could have found the defendant guilty under 145 (b), or it could have found him guilty under 3616 (a).","start":680.257,"stop":694.632,"duration":14.38},{"text":"Not a matter of the prosecutor's discretion.","start":694.632,"stop":697.803,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood you to say that the Washington office sent to the prosecuting attorneys in 177 cases were made about this one (Inaudible) 177 cases with instructions to proceed under 3616?","start":697.803,"stop":712.846,"duration":15.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":712.846,"stop":714.076,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But whose choice was that?","start":714.076,"stop":716.156,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That was the choice of the prosecutor.","start":716.156,"stop":719.331,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And were they prosecuted by information?","start":719.331,"stop":722.002,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that most of them were.","start":722.002,"stop":724.117,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who made those choices?","start":724.117,"stop":724.259,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- there were really some -- that was made by the department, by the prosecutor.","start":724.259,"stop":731.728,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your main position however, as I understand it, and to me it's very important to determine whether its own act.","start":731.728,"stop":738.608,"duration":6.88},{"text":"Your main position is that a detailed consideration which we not yet had at the legislative history of the criminal enforcement of the income tax.","start":738.608,"stop":750.025,"duration":11.42},{"text":"The Government demonstrates 145 (b) as exclusive, the 3616 does not apply to it.","start":750.025,"stop":756.233,"duration":6.21},{"text":"Is that right?","start":756.233,"stop":756.899,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":756.899,"stop":757.987,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's very important too, this is a new position.","start":757.987,"stop":761.263,"duration":3.28},{"text":"And for me, nothing has happened on the fact that stops taking that position.","start":761.263,"stop":765.03,"duration":3.77},{"text":"It's never too late to find out what Congress really did.","start":765.03,"stop":768.57,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think --","start":768.57,"stop":768.716,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't suppose -- I don't suppose it's too late for any of us to do that.","start":768.716,"stop":771.653,"duration":2.94},{"text":"I simply wanted to find out first if we disagreed with your position, if these were the same kind of case as the Berra case.","start":771.653,"stop":779.818,"duration":8.16},{"text":"Of course, if you are wrong all that time and the 3616 does not cover income taxes, it should not be held cover if it doesn't do it.","start":779.818,"stop":792.012,"duration":12.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As many often, we'd leave enough time for the main problem that the Government has now presented which is very foreign to me.","start":792.012,"stop":798.726,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm delighted to see that's reproduced for counsel this time.","start":798.726,"stop":805.573,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's with my information at the counsel's time for my enlightenment.","start":805.573,"stop":809.104,"duration":3.53},{"text":"That's what counsel are here for, to enlighten the Court not to be indulging -- to be indulging it.","start":809.104,"stop":816.611,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, with respect to the legislative history of Section 3616, a section which states back -- which dates back to 1798, our research has indicated there is the gravest doubt as to whether it applies or contended to apply to federal income tax as we have known it since 1913.","start":816.611,"stop":843.545,"duration":26.93},{"text":"Now, back in the civil war days when you have the Acts of 1861, 1862 and 1864, where they included a statute which was very similar to 3616 within the Act itself, I think it is safe to assume that that Act did apply to this civil war income tax which did not have any other sanctions of itself.","start":843.545,"stop":870.76,"duration":27.22},{"text":"And again in 1894, when the income tax law was passed which was held unconstitutional by this Court in the Pollock against Farmers' Loan & Trust Company case.","start":870.76,"stop":884.88,"duration":14.12},{"text":"There again, we had no sanctions within the statute.","start":884.88,"stop":887.91,"duration":3.03},{"text":"So, and it seems fair to assume that the sanctions of section -- had become in 1874, 3179 of the revised statutes was intended to be the specific sanction which would apply to that particular Act.","start":887.91,"stop":906.622,"duration":18.71},{"text":"But when we come down to the War Revenue Act of 1894, which were not an income tax law but a General Revenue Act, that Act had specific penalties and it provided that if any manufacturer or maker makes a false run through declaration, he shall be guilty of a misdemeanor with a sentence of six months in prison or $500 fine or both.","start":906.622,"stop":933.109,"duration":26.49},{"text":"Now, there we had specific penalties applying to that particular Act and it would appear that the general earlier provision of the 1874 revised statutes were superseded pro tanto.","start":933.109,"stop":951.589,"duration":18.48},{"text":"Again in 1909, when that corporation exercised tax of that year measured by corporate income was passed -- it had passed specific penalties for the making of a fraudulent -- false or fraudulent return with intent to defeat the assessment of one year in prison or $1000 fine, which incidentally with the same penalties as those in the 3179 of the revised statutes.","start":951.589,"stop":980.684,"duration":29.09},{"text":"In the Revenue Act of 1913, which is the first of the various revenue acts that followed thereafter and from 1913 to about until 1939, it was the practice of Congress to enact a new revenue act about every two years.","start":980.684,"stop":999.038,"duration":18.35},{"text":"Each of those acts would be a complete reenactment of the income tax laws as they had existed up to that time.","start":999.038,"stop":1009.619,"duration":10.58},{"text":"In the Revenue Act of 1913, the first of such acts, Congress provided that whoever made a false or fraudulent return with intent to defeat the assessment would be guilty of a misdemeanor and subject to a year in the prison on a $2000 fine.","start":1009.619,"stop":1029.034,"duration":19.42},{"text":"The fine in this -- in that Act, the $2000 was greater than the $1000 fine imposed by Section 3179 of the revised statutes.","start":1029.034,"stop":1039.665,"duration":10.63},{"text":"And we think that that indicates that the specific penalty of that particular Act was intended to apply to the crime of income tax evasion rather than the more general provision carrying a lesser penalty.","start":1039.665,"stop":1064.267,"duration":24.6},{"text":"The Revenue Act of 1917 had the same provision as to a false and fraudulent return with intent to defeat an assessment and added a new provision making it a misdemeanor to evade or attempt to evade a tax in any manner.","start":1064.267,"stop":1082.677,"duration":18.41},{"text":"In the Revenue Act of 1918, the law, for the first time prescribed an attempt to evade tax in any manner and we believe that the addition of the words in any manner in that Act made it unnecessary for the law of any further to have references to the evasion and to the filing of the false or fraudulent return.","start":1082.677,"stop":1109.562,"duration":26.88},{"text":"And significantly, the -- that term was dropped in the 1918 Act and is not appeared in any Revenue Act since that time.","start":1109.562,"stop":1123.245,"duration":13.68},{"text":"In the Revenue Act of 1924, the Congress raised the penalties for a willful evasion of income tax from a misdemeanor to a felony.","start":1123.245,"stop":1137.739,"duration":14.49},{"text":"And from that time, 1924 until 1939, the successive Revenue Acts have prescribed an attempt to evade income tax as a felony with no material change in the wording of a statute.","start":1137.739,"stop":1155.464,"duration":17.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it -- but it's still one year, the punishment after 1924?","start":1155.464,"stop":1159.651,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"1924 was five years.","start":1159.651,"stop":1161.331,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Five years, yes.","start":1161.331,"stop":1162.133,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"And it continued that way in each --","start":1162.133,"stop":1163.609,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then you said a a felony, didn't just --","start":1163.609,"stop":1165.43,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, made a felony.","start":1165.43,"stop":1165.505,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a different (Voice Overlap) -- put a different punishment on it.","start":1165.505,"stop":1167.803,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's right, Your Honor.","start":1167.803,"stop":1170.482,"duration":2.68},{"text":"In 19 -- that brings us to 1939 which the -- in -- the year in which the Internal Revenue Code of that year was adopted.","start":1170.482,"stop":1179.317,"duration":8.84},{"text":"That Code is to be distinguished from the 1954 Internal Revenue Code in that it did not purport to be in any sense a -- did not change the law in any respect.","start":1179.317,"stop":1192.999,"duration":13.68},{"text":"It was merely bringing together as the legislator said into one volume laws that have been scattered through a number of volumes.","start":1192.999,"stop":1201.85,"duration":8.85},{"text":"And the fear of the legislators as indicated in the legislative history was that some change in the law might be made inadvertently, most of the discussion on the congressional record relates to whether those fears on the laying of those fears for the sponsors that no change had been made in the revenue laws that existed prior to that time.","start":1201.85,"stop":1226.816,"duration":24.97},{"text":"Of course that is not true at all in the 1954 Code which incorporated any number of amendments.","start":1226.816,"stop":1233.737,"duration":6.92},{"text":"But this was merely a compilation and somewhat along the lines of the changes in the judicial code or referred to by this Court in the Fourco Glass Company case here earlier in this term.","start":1233.737,"stop":1251.664,"duration":17.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there anything turned on the 1939 Code?","start":1251.664,"stop":1256.386,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we want to show that because -- that the bringing of Section 3179 of the revised statutes into the Code and labeling it 3616, did not mean that there was any change in the scope or ambit of the section as it had existed prior to that time.","start":1256.386,"stop":1278.739,"duration":22.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that presuppose of -- does that mean any more than that if you are right, if the Government is right as to what -- as to the construction of the predecessor provision of 145 (b) in the annuals or biannuals of congressional legislation, 1939 didn't effectuate.","start":1278.739,"stop":1298.783,"duration":20.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1298.783,"stop":1299.046,"duration":0.26},{"text":"That's right.","start":1299.046,"stop":1299.608,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you have to establish the relationship of the two sections prior to 1939.","start":1299.608,"stop":1304.581,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's right, sir.","start":1304.581,"stop":1311.022,"duration":6.44},{"text":"We think that a comparison of the Section 3616 with other statutes in pari materia throughout the Code and outside of the Internal Revenue Code will indicate the ludicrous and almost absurd results which would follow if it were to be deemed that the following of a false and fraudulent return with intent to evade tax amounted to no more than a felony.","start":1311.022,"stop":1340.017,"duration":29},{"text":"For example, take Section 145 (a) of the Code which relates to acts of omission of a failure to file a return or to furnish information.","start":1340.017,"stop":1349.723,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Under that section, the penalty is one year in jail with a $10,000 fine.","start":1349.723,"stop":1357.633,"duration":7.91},{"text":"But if the petitioner is right that the offense he committed was only a misdemeanor, his acts of omission would result in a year in jail and a $1000 fine or substantially less penalty than the acts of omission.","start":1357.633,"stop":1373,"duration":15.37},{"text":"Again, with respect to Section 3793 of the Code --","start":1373,"stop":1380.446,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may finish your sentence.","start":1380.446,"stop":1382.69,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"With respect to Section 3793 of the Code, which prescribed the willful aiding or assisting in the preparation of a false or fraudulent return, if the petitioner is correct in his position, the person who assist in the filing -- preparation and filing of such a return will receive a penalty of five years in jail and a $10,000 fine.But the one who actually files the return receives only one year and $1000 fine.","start":1382.69,"stop":1429.694,"duration":47}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1429.694,"stop":1430.806,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Atwood.","start":1430.806,"stop":1433.17,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I have just a few remarks to make.","start":1433.17,"stop":1435.936,"duration":2.77},{"text":"They deal principally with the -- what I consider there and then -- in the administrative approval on the part of Congress in reenacting Section 3616 (a) in the 1954 Code of Section 7207 of the 1954 Code.","start":1435.936,"stop":1452.559,"duration":16.62},{"text":"When Congress did that as I mentioned in my earlier argument specifically stated that it was not changing existing law and Congress of course must have been aware of the fact that the Government had been prosecuting for more than two years prior to the Revenue Act of 1954, many cases under Section 3616 (a) for income tax violations.","start":1452.559,"stop":1472.783,"duration":20.22},{"text":"I've also pointed out that as far back as 1926 in the Noveck case, the Government argued that Section 3616 (a) wasn't applicable to income taxes but it was nevertheless proceeding over a period of years in many cases to argue that it was applicable.","start":1472.783,"stop":1488.693,"duration":15.91},{"text":"In the cases I've cited at page 15 of my reply brief and there are many cases there I've cited.","start":1488.693,"stop":1494.614,"duration":5.92},{"text":"And of course, as late as 1945 in the (Inaudible) case, the Government argued that it was applicable.","start":1494.614,"stop":1499.696,"duration":5.08},{"text":"Certainly, in those cases, the Government was of course consistent throughout that period of time in the time when saying it was applicable.","start":1499.696,"stop":1508.237,"duration":8.54},{"text":"In any simple reading of Section 3616 (a) would indicate that it was applicable.","start":1508.237,"stop":1516.733,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Absent this detailed history which they now say means that it was inapplicable income tax.","start":1516.733,"stop":1523.213,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That Congress -- does 3616 in your view had any function at all?","start":1523.213,"stop":1529.839,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Does it apply to a situation at all in the protection of the revenue --","start":1529.839,"stop":1537.618,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice --","start":1537.618,"stop":1538.144,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If 145 (b) should have sowed the field with reference to income tax.","start":1538.144,"stop":1545.535,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I feel this way, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, that it supplements Section 145 (b) in that, it provides a lesser penalty for what Congress may have thought was a smaller offense.","start":1545.535,"stop":1555.052,"duration":9.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":1555.052,"stop":1556.704,"duration":1.65},{"text":"That it -- I understand that.","start":1556.704,"stop":1558.217,"duration":1.51},{"text":"What I want to know is assume 145 (b) is to be given the restrictive and exclusive scope that is now contended for by the Government.","start":1558.217,"stop":1571.156,"duration":12.94},{"text":"Would 3616 go to sleep and have no incidents at all?","start":1571.156,"stop":1578.328,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that would be the effect of it, yes.","start":1578.328,"stop":1580.108,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as to these things but wouldn't they -- would it apply to other situations?","start":1580.108,"stop":1585.818,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"In then --","start":1585.818,"stop":1586.044,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"For me it must be a very strong argument.","start":1586.044,"stop":1588.17,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would --","start":1588.17,"stop":1588.341,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If it were to exist (Voice Overlap) --","start":1588.341,"stop":1588.97,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it would still exist because as Section 3616 applies to false testimony and applies to failure to give -- produce records and all those things which do apply to income taxes.","start":1588.97,"stop":1600.464,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think --","start":1600.464,"stop":1600.661,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know whether it follow --","start":1600.661,"stop":1600.991,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I've put my question.","start":1600.991,"stop":1602.217,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1602.217,"stop":1602.533,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would there be no set of circumstances to which 1616 could be applied to which 145 (b) wouldn't apply?","start":1602.533,"stop":1612.944,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't think of any now.","start":1612.944,"stop":1614.22,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I think it would be ineffective when applied anything according to the Government's argument.","start":1614.22,"stop":1618.555,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think -- for me it's a very important point.","start":1618.555,"stop":1620.988,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1620.988,"stop":1621.313,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's one thing to say that the Government is arguing for a construction that would wipe out a section quite a different argument to say that there are two sections which have separate spheres of activity.","start":1621.313,"stop":1634.283,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not think the argument had had a separate sphere of activity.","start":1634.283,"stop":1636.591,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand they do.","start":1636.591,"stop":1636.725,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"The argument is repealed.","start":1636.725,"stop":1638.266,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me.","start":1638.266,"stop":1638.86,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they argue, I believe --","start":1638.86,"stop":1639.834,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We deal as to what 145 (b) covered but not as to everything.","start":1639.834,"stop":1644.651,"duration":4.82},{"text":"It isn't an empty thing thereafter, a collection of words with no -- nothing on which you can talk.","start":1644.651,"stop":1656.318,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I rely on the fact that the Government was prosecuting for many years under Section 3616 (a) and Congress knew that and reenacted Section 720 -- 3616 (a) as part of 7207 of the Revenue Act of 1954 which clearly dealt with income taxes.","start":1656.318,"stop":1673.45,"duration":17.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You said for many years, what --","start":1673.45,"stop":1674.88,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"That's from 1952 to 1954 and then in the prior years, the -- in the many cases which I've cited at page 15 of my brief, they argued that it was applicable to income taxes and Congress presumed they could be aware of that argument.","start":1674.88,"stop":1693.169,"duration":18.29},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1693.169,"stop":1721.753,"duration":28.58}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - May 02, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13286","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 430, Sam Achilli, Petitioner, versus United States of America and Number 834, Sam Achilli versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":16.579,"duration":16.58},{"text":"Mr. Atwood.","start":16.579,"stop":17.641,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":17.641,"stop":18.829,"duration":1.19},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":18.829,"stop":22.668,"duration":3.84},{"text":"The petitioner in this case was indicted and convicted of willfully and knowingly attempting to evade a large part of his income tax with violation of section 145 (b) of the Internal Revenue Code for the years 1946, 1947 and 1948.","start":22.668,"stop":44.332,"duration":21.66},{"text":"The trial court imposed a sentence of two years on each count, which would run concurrently and a $2000 fine on each count or a total of $6000.","start":44.332,"stop":56.699,"duration":12.37},{"text":"On appeal to the Seventh Circuit, the Court of Appeals reversed this to the first count for insufficient evidence and sustained as to the remaining two counts for the years 1947 and 1948.","start":56.699,"stop":70.554,"duration":13.86},{"text":"A petition for rehearing was filed which was denied wherein in that petition for the first there was raised the question of the overlap of Sections 145 (b) and Section 3616(a) of the Internal Revenue Code.","start":70.554,"stop":87.497,"duration":16.94},{"text":"A petition for certiorari was denied on November 19, 1956 and later withdrawn.","start":87.497,"stop":94.345,"duration":6.85},{"text":"Subsequent to the denial of petition for certiorari, the case was brought back to the District Court for resentencing under the mandate of the Court of Appeals.","start":94.345,"stop":103.319,"duration":8.97},{"text":"At that time, a further motion was filed for correction and reduction of sentence.","start":103.319,"stop":108.526,"duration":5.21},{"text":"The substantial -- filed the motion.","start":108.526,"stop":109.846,"duration":1.32},{"text":"It was based upon the overlap of section 3616 (a) and 145 (b).","start":109.846,"stop":116.082,"duration":6.24},{"text":"The Court denied the motion with respect to the overlap but reduced the sentence to one year on each of the remaining counts to run concurrently and fixed the fine of $1000 on each count to be accumulated or a total of $2000.","start":116.082,"stop":130.393,"duration":14.31},{"text":"The matter was brought before the Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit and while there, the Court -- this Court was dually -- one on the denial of certiorari and both cases are now before this Court.","start":130.393,"stop":144.563,"duration":14.17},{"text":"The contention which we make in this case is that an attempt to evade taxes within the meaning of Section 145 (b) is the same and identical thence provide in Section 3616 (a) to file a false and fraudulent return with intent to defeat and evade the tax.","start":144.563,"stop":166.761,"duration":22.2},{"text":"The indictment which was filed against the petitioner in this case alleged that he willfully and knowingly attempted to defeat and he attempted to avoid the -- and evade the payment tax by the filing of a false and fraudulent return.","start":166.761,"stop":180.317,"duration":13.56},{"text":"I think the Government admits the identity of the offenses when it states at page 33 of its brief, the following, \"In the instant case as in Berra versus United States 351 U.S.131 and indeed almost every case prosecuted under section 145 (b), the proof that the defendant willfully attempted to evade taxes by filing a false return is identical without that required to prove that he filed a false return with intent to evade tax in violation of section 3616 (a).","start":180.317,"stop":215.91,"duration":35.59},{"text":"The consequences of that assumption, I've set forth in the -- the main brief, which we filed in this clause to the effect that there is an identity of the offenses and there cannot be a dual offense or double conviction for a misdemeanor and for the penalty.","start":215.91,"stop":235.978,"duration":20.07},{"text":"The Government, approximately one week before we are about to file our brief in this case, the time fixed by this Court, made a completely, new position, took a completely new position with respect to section 3616 (a) to the effect that section – that that section did not apply to income taxes.","start":235.978,"stop":258.247,"duration":22.27},{"text":"That change of position, I'd like to devote a few minutes to because it seems to me to be quite important with respect to the history of this litigation and of the statutes involved.","start":258.247,"stop":268.717,"duration":10.47},{"text":"When this Costello case was before this Court and which it is at this term, the Government admitted that Section 3616 (a) applied to income taxes and stated as a matter fact that it put clearly and therefore it applied to income taxes.","start":268.717,"stop":285.988,"duration":17.27},{"text":"The Government in the Dillon case in the Eighth Circuit had argued that 3616 (a) did not applied to income taxes and was successful in securing a ruling by the Eighth Circuit to the effect that 3616 (a) did not apply to income taxes.","start":285.988,"stop":314.171,"duration":28.18},{"text":"The Government in its -- our -- our position to -- position for certiorari in that case disavowed holding of the Eighth Circuit and said that 3616 (a) did apply to income taxes.","start":314.171,"stop":325.977,"duration":11.81},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it prepared an appendix to a brief in the later cases, one of which was (Inaudible) case which is also pending before this Court, in which it prepared an appendix to that brief and which was send around to the various District Attorneys throughout the United States to be used in what we call boilerplate in cases, the -- involving the same subject.","start":325.977,"stop":353.139,"duration":27.16},{"text":"In other words, urging the Court's --","start":353.139,"stop":354.399,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What did they -- what did they say to their -- their District Attorneys in that regard?","start":354.399,"stop":359.966,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"In this appendix, Your Honors, that -- Mr. Chief Justice, is to the effect that the --","start":359.966,"stop":364.301,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I always read the amount of it.","start":364.301,"stop":366.463,"duration":2.16},{"text":"I don't ask you to read a lot of it --","start":366.463,"stop":367.67,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":367.67,"stop":367.92,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but did they -- did they in effect urge them to -- to act upon 3616 as though it was applicable to the income tax laws?","start":367.92,"stop":377.972,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true Your Honor.","start":377.972,"stop":378.734,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And furthermore, they cited the same historical material in which they -- they call materials that they cite here, in this case.","start":378.734,"stop":386.481,"duration":7.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't suggest that -- you don't suggest that in the estoppel, do you?","start":386.481,"stop":389.766,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not, Your Honor.","start":389.766,"stop":390.769,"duration":1},{"text":"Not at all, not at all.","start":390.769,"stop":392.125,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You just say it's very persuasive.","start":392.125,"stop":393.266,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I say it goes to part of the history, which I like to bring out as we go along with respect to that subject.","start":393.266,"stop":399.373,"duration":6.11},{"text":"As a matter of fact the -- the Eighth Circuit in the Dillon case also stated that Section 7207 of the 1954 Code which is the counterpart of Section 3616 (a) of the 1939 Code applied to income taxes.","start":399.373,"stop":420.007,"duration":20.63},{"text":"The Court -- or failed in that case to take Congress into the fact that two reports that Congress, the Senate and The House with respect to the 1954 Code specifically stated that the Section 7207 was not intended to make any change in existing law.","start":420.007,"stop":442.381,"duration":22.37},{"text":"The -- the Government also as far back as 1952 admits that they have been prosecuting these cases under Section 3616 (a).","start":442.381,"stop":456.411,"duration":14.03},{"text":"They say that prior to that time there was no judicial holding that 3616 (a) did not apply to income taxes or any innovation to that effect.","start":456.411,"stop":466.645,"duration":10.23},{"text":"However, they do not disclose in their brief --","start":466.645,"stop":469.512,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"By prosecuting -- I take it that you mean that sentences were imposed were in 3616.","start":469.512,"stop":476.4,"duration":6.89}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Or an information file (Voice Overlap) --","start":476.4,"stop":477.615,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or in the Commission.","start":477.615,"stop":478.49,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":478.49,"stop":479.519,"duration":1.03},{"text":"There were -- they say that up prior -- prior to 1952 there were no cases holding that 3616 did not apply to income taxes and rely solely on the Dillon case as indicating that as the first holding in which the Court -- they are determined that 3616 (a) did not apply.","start":479.519,"stop":497.1,"duration":17.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand correctly.","start":497.1,"stop":500.803,"duration":3.7},{"text":"When you say it didn't apply, a prosecution or the conflict that is in -- in question here, your contention is it falls both within section 145 and 3616, is that right?","start":500.803,"stop":516.636,"duration":15.83}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":516.636,"stop":517.716,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, to say it was -- it was -- it could be -- if it was prosecuted under 3616, merely means to me legal significance of that statement is that the sentence that was imposed, the limits of -- of sentence provided for by 3616 was given by the judges, the various -- in those prosecutions.","start":517.716,"stop":539.195,"duration":21.48},{"text":"Does it mean anything else?","start":539.195,"stop":540.517,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"It means this that the District Attorneys in filing an information against the taxpayer relied on section 3616 (a).","start":540.517,"stop":549.349,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You see it as the indictment of the information endorsed.","start":549.349,"stop":551.279,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Information there -- that's correct, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":551.279,"stop":554.473,"duration":3.19},{"text":"There were -- there would be no indictment involving 3616 (a) because of its being a misdemeanor.","start":554.473,"stop":561.204,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean it has to belie information?","start":561.204,"stop":563.556,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so, Your Honor.","start":563.556,"stop":569.11,"duration":5.55},{"text":"The -- prior to -- well, then the Government proceeds in its brief to disclose a considerable amount manner of statistics showing that since 1952, a 177 cases have been prosecuted under section 3616 (a).","start":569.11,"stop":585.068,"duration":15.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I must trouble you again.","start":585.068,"stop":586.427,"duration":1.36},{"text":"Does that mean that in none of those of cases there were grand jury proceedings – preceding the trial on the merits?","start":586.427,"stop":593.575,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"The information disclosed in their --","start":593.575,"stop":595.044,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I can hardly believe that.","start":595.044,"stop":596.377,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Their brief in the case they were by information.","start":596.377,"stop":598.573,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my question is a little different.","start":598.573,"stop":602.293,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How many cases did you say Mr. --","start":602.293,"stop":603.955,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"177, Your Honor.","start":603.955,"stop":605.588,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice.","start":605.588,"stop":606.401,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless -- unless prosecutors differ greatly when I knew at first hand time something about them its not uncommon for prosecutors to be wrong in the selection of the statute.","start":606.401,"stop":617.616,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"However, prior to 1952, the Government itself urged in many cases which it cites at page 39 of its brief.","start":617.616,"stop":628.652,"duration":11.04},{"text":"I believe its 39, to the effect that Section 3616 (a) is applicable to income taxes.","start":628.652,"stop":638.215,"duration":9.56},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it cites a case dated back in 1945 in which it was urged the Koppelman case.","start":638.215,"stop":644.341,"duration":6.13},{"text":"In which it was heard that the 3616 (a) applied to income tax proceedings where the petitioner there was seeking probation.","start":644.341,"stop":659.564,"duration":15.22},{"text":"And the District Attorney opposed probation on the ground that he had filed a false and fraudulent return in violation of Section 3616 (a).","start":659.564,"stop":672.691,"duration":13.13},{"text":"The position we take with respect to that is that it seems to me that the Government at this late stage, approximately a week prior to the filing of our return, with this change of position feels and must feel that unless they are successful with respect to that contention, they have lost this case.","start":672.691,"stop":698.709,"duration":26.02},{"text":"I'd like to advert now directly to the history of Section 3616 (a).","start":698.709,"stop":704.932,"duration":6.22},{"text":"But I think it's -- the crux of this whole case and I think the Government has pitched its own case on that argument.","start":704.932,"stop":713.618,"duration":8.69},{"text":"Certainly, that Congress itself in our brief history of the matter is set forth at page 3 of our brief.","start":713.618,"stop":722.07,"duration":8.45},{"text":"The Congress it's -- of our reply brief, that Congress itself as stated in the 1954 Code that the derivation of Section 3616 (a) or -- or Section 7207 of the 1954 Code is Section 3616 (a).","start":722.07,"stop":736.439,"duration":14.37},{"text":"In the 1939 Code, that Congress has stated that the derivation of Section 3616 (a) is Section 3179 of Revised Statutes.","start":736.439,"stop":747.173,"duration":10.73},{"text":"The two reports of the House and the Senate, which I adverted to you before, both specifically state that the 1954 Code with respect to Section 7207 did not change the existing law.","start":747.173,"stop":765.74,"duration":18.57},{"text":"Now, the question is then I think to back and see the antecedence of Section 3616.","start":765.74,"stop":775.033,"duration":9.29},{"text":"3616 had its derivation in Revised Statutes of Section 3179 which first appeared in Revised Statutes of 1874.","start":775.033,"stop":790.614,"duration":15.58},{"text":"The predecessor of that section was the Act of 1798 as shown by the materials which were submitted by the Government and which applied -- there was, of course, no income tax at that time.","start":790.614,"stop":804.405,"duration":13.79},{"text":"In 1861 and 1862, there was an income tax.","start":804.405,"stop":807.35,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And the Government admits that section -- that the predecessor of Section 3179 applied to the income tax provisions of the Act of 1861 and 1864.","start":807.35,"stop":821.843,"duration":14.49},{"text":"In 1864, Congress passed a supplement to the revenue laws, which contained certain administrative provisions, one of which was Section 15.","start":821.843,"stop":833.729,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Section 15 later became Section 3179 of Revised Statutes.","start":833.729,"stop":839.59,"duration":5.86},{"text":"It reads as follows, \"Whenever any person delivers or discloses to the collector or deputy any false and fraudulent list, return account or statement with intent to defeat or evade evaluation, enumeration or assessment intended to be made or being dully summoned to appear to testify or to appear and produce such books as aforesaid, neglects and so forth shall be fined not exceeding $1000 or imprisoned -- or imprisoned not exceeding one year.”","start":839.59,"stop":875.323,"duration":35.73},{"text":"The Government urges that that provision was superseded by later legislation with respect to income taxes and relies upon the Act of 1898 as it started.","start":875.323,"stop":886.859,"duration":11.54},{"text":"It states that the Act of 1898 marked the resumption of a congressional policy, which was in -- though not in effect in 1874 had been followed ever since of incorporating, under each Revenue Act, specific criminal penalties.","start":886.859,"stop":903.155,"duration":16.3},{"text":"Now, it relies on the Act of 1898, which provided that if any manufacturer shall make any false or untrue declaration, such person shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor.","start":903.155,"stop":914.3,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Now, it seems to me quite obvious that that provision could not apply to the exclusion of Section 3179 because it did not require a proof of an intent to evade tax which was one of the requirements of Section 3179.","start":914.3,"stop":931.293,"duration":16.99},{"text":"The -- there is therefore, a different case -- a different proof required under the 1898 Act as compared with Section 3179.","start":931.293,"stop":941.015,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Atwood, do I correctly understand the Government's position is not that 3616 in terms would not apply to this offense.","start":941.015,"stop":950.779,"duration":9.76},{"text":"But rather that later legislation has indicated a congressional intention to supercede the purposes of prosecution of this offense?","start":950.779,"stop":961.918,"duration":11.14},{"text":"That statute with the felony statute.","start":961.918,"stop":965.612,"duration":3.69},{"text":"I -- I don't -- do you understand the Government to argue that in terms 3616 would not apply at this time?","start":965.612,"stop":971.825,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":971.825,"stop":972.064,"duration":0.24},{"text":"I think that's the position of their --","start":972.064,"stop":972.778,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You do?","start":972.778,"stop":974.06,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's their whole case, Your Honor.","start":974.06,"stop":975.409,"duration":1.35},{"text":"That there was a repeal, pro tanto as they say of section 31 --","start":975.409,"stop":982.637,"duration":7.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that --","start":982.637,"stop":982.806,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"So, it means that it would have applied only three other different taxes.","start":982.806,"stop":985.983,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what they pay.","start":985.983,"stop":987.26,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of fact, the official (Inaudible) tax that they refer to is covered by specific legislation, which is referred to in the reply brief of the Government.","start":987.26,"stop":994.652,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps, I should have ask the Government the question but I -- I followed your argument.","start":994.652,"stop":998.559,"duration":3.91},{"text":"I thought it different -- that your impression is different from mine of what the Government is saying.","start":998.559,"stop":1003.126,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"I do feel that they -- they have the -- they've taken the position of 3616 does not applied to income taxes at all.","start":1003.126,"stop":1009.695,"duration":6.57},{"text":"Even --","start":1009.695,"stop":1010.22,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That we have nothing else in the way of legislation or history or anything else but on the face of it, it would not apply.","start":1010.22,"stop":1016.924,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":1016.924,"stop":1017.492,"duration":0.57},{"text":"They did apply to income tax cases when there were income tax laws in effect but they had taken the position that when Congress was about the specific criminal penalties and later legislation, they did so to the exclusion of Section 3179.","start":1017.492,"stop":1030.678,"duration":13.19},{"text":"And they start with this 1898 Act as indicating that.","start":1030.678,"stop":1034.037,"duration":3.36},{"text":"And as I just pointed out the 1898 Act was a much narrower Act.","start":1034.037,"stop":1038.769,"duration":4.73},{"text":"It provided a smaller penalty.","start":1038.769,"stop":1040.55,"duration":1.78},{"text":"It didn't have the qualification of intent to evade which was in the -- in the 3179 provision.","start":1040.55,"stop":1046.68,"duration":6.13},{"text":"Nor did it have the later -- the other requirement in the section 3179 which was that any person summoned to testify or to produce books shall be guilty of a misdemeanor.","start":1046.68,"stop":1056.937,"duration":10.26},{"text":"That was not in the 1898 Act.","start":1056.937,"stop":1058.468,"duration":1.53},{"text":"So, obviously in my opinion the both were -- were supplementary to each.","start":1058.468,"stop":1063.51,"duration":5.04},{"text":"They complimented each other.","start":1063.51,"stop":1065.684,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Then the Government proceeds to say that the 1909 Act set a pattern with respect to the subject.","start":1065.684,"stop":1071.597,"duration":5.91},{"text":"The 1909 Act was, of course, not an income tax but a tax, an excise tax on the corporations by measured by income.","start":1071.597,"stop":1087.224,"duration":15.63},{"text":"And that tax also was very limited, that specific criminal provisioning -- provision which was contained in paragraph 8 of the Act of 1909 provided that any person authorized by law to make, render, sign or verify any return who makes any false and fraudulent return or statement with intent to evade or defeat the tax imposed shall be guilty of a misdemeanor.","start":1087.224,"stop":1111.842,"duration":24.62},{"text":"Well there again, there was very limited scope to section -- paragraph 8 of the Act of 1909 in that it applied only to persons who were required to render, sign or verify the return.","start":1111.842,"stop":1121.964,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Whereas that Section 3179 applied to anyone who was required -- who -- who -- disclosed or delivered a return to the collector.","start":1121.964,"stop":1130.408,"duration":8.44},{"text":"It also applied as I've just mentioned, to anyone who supplied -- who were refused to produce books or to testify.","start":1130.408,"stop":1138.399,"duration":7.99},{"text":"That issue was not covered by the Act of 1909.","start":1138.399,"stop":1141.065,"duration":2.67},{"text":"And therefore again, both Acts could exist together and apply to the income tax proceeding.","start":1141.065,"stop":1147.749,"duration":6.68},{"text":"The Government says then that there were no specific legislation thereafter which indicated that the -- the Section 3179 applied to income tax proceedings because thereafter, commerce legislated specifically on the subject.","start":1147.749,"stop":1170.797,"duration":23.05},{"text":"However, that is not the case.","start":1170.797,"stop":1172.858,"duration":2.06},{"text":"Actually, there were only two Revenue Acts between 1909 and 1928, which specifically dealt with income taxes.","start":1172.858,"stop":1182.101,"duration":9.24},{"text":"That was -- the very first one was the Revenue Act of 1913.","start":1182.101,"stop":1186.818,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Now, that Act too is very limited in scope.","start":1186.818,"stop":1195.533,"duration":8.71},{"text":"I like to refer the language of that which appears at page 17 of our main brief, which begins that if any person liable to make the return or pay the tax shall neglect to refuse and any person required by law to make, render and sign which is the same language which was contained in the 1909 Act.","start":1195.533,"stop":1217.234,"duration":21.7},{"text":"And again, was limited to persons who were required to file a return and didn't apply, for instance, to an accountant who would deliver a list or a statement to the collector or the director which would prove to be fraudulent or false.","start":1217.234,"stop":1231.314,"duration":14.08},{"text":"So that again, Section 3179 would equally apply to a criminal undertaking on the part of a taxpayer or a representative of the taxpayer under the 1913 Act.","start":1231.314,"stop":1247.114,"duration":15.8},{"text":"Then to the 1913 Act, it didn't contain the language, which was contained in Section 3179 relating to the production of books or the testifying before an internal revenue agent or representative.","start":1247.114,"stop":1260.959,"duration":13.85},{"text":"The Government then says that the Revenue Act of 1918 is an evidence of Congress intending that its specific criminal provisions shall be applied exclusively to income tax proceedings.","start":1260.959,"stop":1274.594,"duration":13.63},{"text":"There again, we have a very limited provision in the -- in the criminal provisions of the Revenue Act of 1918.","start":1274.594,"stop":1282.338,"duration":7.74},{"text":"The Revenue Act of 1918 provided that anyone who attempts to evade or defeat the tax imposed by that chapter shall be guilty of a misdemeanor.","start":1282.338,"stop":1298.672,"duration":16.33},{"text":"They added the words \"in any manner.\"","start":1298.672,"stop":1301.256,"duration":2.58},{"text":"In other words, anyone who attempts in any manner to defeat or evade the tax shall be guilty for a misdemeanor.","start":1301.256,"stop":1308.187,"duration":6.93},{"text":"But there again, the use of the words \"in any manner,\" would not enlarge the meaning of the Act because the Congress is not required to set forth the details of -- of the manner in which an evasion shall take place.","start":1308.187,"stop":1321.702,"duration":13.52},{"text":"So that the Revenue Act of 1917 which dealt with the same subject but which left out the words in any manner would have the same scope with the 1918 Act.","start":1321.702,"stop":1331.981,"duration":10.28},{"text":"The Congress it seems to me decided in 1918 to punish attempts as such which are to distinguished from the merely -- from the mere filing of a false and fraudulent return which was still a misdemeanor under Section 3179 which provided however, only $1000 fine.","start":1331.981,"stop":1360.685,"duration":28.7},{"text":"In other words, in the Revenue Act 1918, Congress decided to make the penalty for attempts a more serious offense and made the punishment $10,000 but still provided it would be a misdemeanor.","start":1360.685,"stop":1373.585,"duration":12.9},{"text":"I think the distinction between an attempt to evade tax is to be -- is -- is -- is to -- it's very important in this case because in the -- those cases in which the Government has relied upon the attempts provision of Section 145 (b) and possibly this section in 1918 Act, it has always delineated the attempts which the taxpayer has -- is carrying out for the purpose of evading his tax.","start":1373.585,"stop":1401.369,"duration":27.78},{"text":"For instance, he has concealed assets.He has made false entries in his books.","start":1401.369,"stop":1406.476,"duration":5.11},{"text":"He has given false testimony to a revenue agent or he has withheld transactions from his records or in any of the variety of ways depending upon the genius of a taxpayer to attempt to evade the tax as distinguished from filing a return.","start":1406.476,"stop":1422.188,"duration":15.71},{"text":"In those cases, in 1918, the Congress said, “Where you attempt to do these things, commit this affirmative acts, we will make the punishment $10,000 and still keep so to speak, Section 3179 and apply to the filing of a false and fraudulent return”, would intend to evade the tax.","start":1422.188,"stop":1442.72,"duration":20.53},{"text":"Congress apparently believing that the two sections did coexist, if the Section 3179 were applied to what the Government later called “minor cases” because the Government has admitted in this case, that they have prosecuted for over five years individuals under Section 3616 for \"minor\" cases.","start":1442.72,"stop":1464.292,"duration":21.57},{"text":"Now, this would still even attack the Revenue Act of -- even attack Section 3179.","start":1464.292,"stop":1476.795,"duration":12.5},{"text":"I also want to point out that in all of these cases where the Congress was enacting legislation, it was also amending the Revised Statutes.","start":1476.795,"stop":1486.985,"duration":10.19},{"text":"And that it was amending Revised Statutes, which were right alongside of Section 3179 but never at anytime amended Section 3179 or indicated that it was refilling Section 3179.","start":1486.985,"stop":1500.59,"duration":13.61},{"text":"Then comes along the 1924 Act which reverted it to the language of the 1917 Act and apply to attempts to evade tax and referred it to two or three accounts and made it a felony.","start":1500.59,"stop":1514.154,"duration":13.56},{"text":"However, that Act did not apply to income taxes alone.","start":1514.154,"stop":1517.382,"duration":3.23},{"text":"It applied to all forms of taxes.","start":1517.382,"stop":1519.941,"duration":2.56},{"text":"And I'd like to call the Court's attention to the language which appeared in the Government's brief at page 26 on what -- where it makes reference to the 1924 Act.","start":1519.941,"stop":1534.315,"duration":14.37},{"text":"And states in the income tax field, the provision first appearing in the 1924 Act, that \"Any person who willfully attempts in any manner to evade or defeat any tax imposed by this chapter or the payment, thereof, shall be guilty of a felony.\"","start":1534.315,"stop":1548.309,"duration":13.99},{"text":"Now, the word \"chapter\" does not appear in the Act.","start":1548.309,"stop":1550.906,"duration":2.6},{"text":"The word actually is \"Act\".","start":1550.906,"stop":1552.304,"duration":1.4},{"text":"So that should read any tax imposed by this Act.","start":1552.304,"stop":1555.278,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Then counsel went on in its brief to quote, from the late Justice Jackson concerning that section being the capstone of our system of sanctions.","start":1555.278,"stop":1565.872,"duration":10.59},{"text":"I think the reference there is -- is erroneous because in the 1924 Act -- the 1924 or the penal provisions did not relate only to income tax but to all forms of tax.","start":1565.872,"stop":1585.029,"duration":19.16},{"text":"If the Court please, I like to reserve partly 10 minutes for rebuttal.","start":1585.029,"stop":1591.675,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You have five minutes.","start":1591.675,"stop":1593.148,"duration":1.47},{"text":"That's according to length --","start":1593.148,"stop":1593.731,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Five more.","start":1593.731,"stop":1594.547,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but you may reserve that.","start":1594.547,"stop":1595.547,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Peter B. Atwood","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":1595.547,"stop":1598.494,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rice.","start":1598.494,"stop":1602.737,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Please the Court.","start":1602.737,"stop":1603.92,"duration":1.18},{"text":"The number of briefs of amicus curiae which have been filed in this case, there are some evidence of the importance of the case and as far as the revenue collection system is concerned, of course, the downgrading of the criminal sanctions from the status of a felony to that of a misdemeanor is a matter of extreme importance.","start":1603.92,"stop":1632.164,"duration":28.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you start, Mr. Rice, would you tell me whether we have nothing but 3616 to look at?","start":1632.164,"stop":1639.172,"duration":7.01},{"text":"Would it or would it not on its face cover the offense charge?","start":1639.172,"stop":1642.956,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Section 145 (b) did not exist?","start":1642.956,"stop":1646.475,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Just looking at 3616 without anything else.","start":1646.475,"stop":1651.326,"duration":4.85},{"text":"That's all we have.","start":1651.326,"stop":1652.326,"duration":1},{"text":"Would it on its face cover the offense charge here?","start":1652.326,"stop":1654.852,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our position is that section --","start":1654.852,"stop":1656.862,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know what your position is.","start":1656.862,"stop":1658.523,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"There has been --","start":1658.523,"stop":1659.181,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to know whether it would or wouldn't on its face.","start":1659.181,"stop":1661.521,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"It appears on its face to cover the offense charge and that I think is the reason why over a period extending back to 19 --","start":1661.521,"stop":1668.281,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1668.281,"stop":1669.25,"duration":0.97},{"text":"Now, your position -- your position is that the legislative history will establish that return as used there did not include income tax return, is that it?","start":1669.25,"stop":1678.974,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right, Your Honor.","start":1678.974,"stop":1679.669,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1679.669,"stop":1682.162,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"If there is anything that has distinguished the tax collection system in the United States from that in foreign, in any foreign countries is the seriousness of which the criminal sanctions imposed in the United States have been viewed.","start":1682.162,"stop":1702.403,"duration":20.24},{"text":"This Court in the Spies case has referred to the felony sanctions as the capstone of a system designed to meet every offense against the revenue laws.","start":1702.403,"stop":1715.241,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And we think that the system was deliberately intended to impose felony sanctions as evidenced by the eight successive Acts of Congress culminating in the Internal Revenue Code of 1939.","start":1715.241,"stop":1734.617,"duration":19.38},{"text":"Now, I would like to say a few words, at the outset as to the practice within the Department of Justice with respect to the application of Section 3616.","start":1734.617,"stop":1747.798,"duration":13.18},{"text":"That section as far as income tax is concerned, of laying -- laid in a disregarded form for many years and had not been applied as a matter of policy with respect to income tax prosecutions.","start":1747.798,"stop":1767.131,"duration":19.33},{"text":"There had been an occasional reference to what does in the Koppelman case in 1945 in connection with whether or not a man had violated the terms of his probation.","start":1767.131,"stop":1780.037,"duration":12.91},{"text":"But as far as prosecution policy is concerned, the department had not authorized prosecutions under Section 3616 at anytime prior to the middle part of 1952.","start":1780.037,"stop":1794.598,"duration":14.56},{"text":"And the reason for it -- that it did that at that time was this, in the post war period with the great increase in tax rates and the great number of great increase in the number of taxpayers, it was obvious that the great bulk of the income was coming and had to come from those who were in the middle-income brackets and the small-income brackets.","start":1794.598,"stop":1820.372,"duration":25.77},{"text":"And the Internal Revenue service felt that a strict enforcement policy with respect to both the middle-income and low-income brackets was necessary in order to ensure the proper collection of the revenue.","start":1820.372,"stop":1833.444,"duration":13.07},{"text":"So, the result was that beginning in the late 1940's and early 1950's, the Department of Justice began to receive, in very substantial numbers, a large number of cases in which against taxpayers, recommending felony prosecutions.","start":1833.444,"stop":1852.357,"duration":18.91},{"text":"In some of these cases, the amount of tax involved was no more than a hundred dollars and the amounts in -- in very substantial of the cases was very small.","start":1852.357,"stop":1868.206,"duration":15.85},{"text":"At that time, the Department was proceeding on a -- on the basis of felony prosecutions in all cases and the cases continue to be send out for criminal prosecution although some of them are amounted in tax, no more than a $100.","start":1868.206,"stop":1885.01,"duration":16.8},{"text":"As you could well imagine, the -- the these cases met with considerable resistance on the part of the United States District Courts and on the part of the United States Attorneys in the various districts.","start":1885.01,"stop":1898.875,"duration":13.87},{"text":"There were complaints that the District Courts were being turned into police courts, that we were getting back into the prohibition days and that something had to be done about the flow of these small cases, which was reaching the courts.","start":1898.875,"stop":1912.702,"duration":13.83},{"text":"So, casting about in an effort to meet this situation and in an effort to make the punishment fit the offense, recourse was had to Section 3616 (a) of the Code which I said a moment appeared on its face and in general terms to apply to all tax offenses including the income tax.","start":1912.702,"stop":1939.944,"duration":27.24},{"text":"So, beginning at that time about 7% of the cases each year was sent out for prosecution under 3616 (a) instead of 145 (b) of the felony provisions.","start":1939.944,"stop":1954.527,"duration":14.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's been sent out from where?","start":1954.527,"stop":1956.205,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"From the Department of -- here in Washington to the United States Attorneys.","start":1956.205,"stop":1960.049,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What could they talk to him whether to proceed there for a felony or misdemeanor?","start":1960.049,"stop":1964.159,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Instructing them to proceed under Section 3616 (a) --","start":1964.159,"stop":1967.673,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As a misdemeanor from (Voice Overlap) --","start":1967.673,"stop":1968.74,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"As a misdemeanor -- yes.","start":1968.74,"stop":1970.561,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In what percentage did you say?","start":1970.561,"stop":1972.324,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"It's about 7%.","start":1972.324,"stop":1973.566,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"70?","start":1973.566,"stop":1974.293,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Seven.","start":1974.293,"stop":1974.839,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Seven --","start":1974.839,"stop":1975.79,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of the entire number of cases.","start":1975.79,"stop":1979.391,"duration":3.6},{"text":"Now, in the majority of these cases, the proceedings were by information but in a fairly substantial number, then the proceedings were also by -- or were by indictment rather than by information.","start":1979.391,"stop":1996.849,"duration":17.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it there were number of convictions then under it or (Voice Overlap) --","start":1996.849,"stop":1999.285,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Charles K. Rice","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1999.285,"stop":2000.171,"duration":0.89},{"text":"The figures are set forth in our brief at page 14 and 15 --","start":2000.171,"stop":2006.138,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess -- we'll recess now, Mr. --","start":2006.138,"stop":2009.761,"duration":3.62}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"May 2, 1957","petitioner":"Achilli","respondent":"United States","docket":"430","citation":"353 US 373 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/353/373","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 27, 1957"}